A 53-year-old man manual worker with a 13-year history of gout in his right hallux presented to his general practitioner with right knee pain, stiffness, and giving way with no history of trauma. He had been taking allopurinol for 11 years. He drank 10 to 12 units of alcohol per week and his body mass index was 24.4. On examination, he had anterior knee pain and crepitus was felt from the patellofemoral joint. He had a range of motion from 0 to 90 degrees.
